tudies contend there is a liberal bias in the media, a progovernment bias, or a bias in favor of advertisers and business interests. Through his analysis, DiMaggio is the first to systematically examine all of these competing interpretations. He concludes that reporters tailor stories to corporate and government interests, but argues that the ability to "manufacture consent" from the public in favor of these elite views is far from guaranteed. According to DiMaggio, citizens often make use of their own personal experiences and prior attitudes to challenge official narratives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aMass media. 0aPublic opinionxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aPublic opinionxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPublic opinion. 4aCommunication : Political Communication. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Mass Media. 4aHistory : American History. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2017z978311149102840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438463469423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438463469/original  a978-3-11-149102-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles